h representations signal a profound moral ambivalence towards the socio-economic process inherent in capitalist economy. Using a range of examples, from Surinamese zombies to American horror films, it demonstrates the extent to which evil imagery is linked to a fear of excess, particularly in situations where people find themselves, or perceive themselves, to be peripheral to the centers of political, economic, and cultural power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aBelief and doubt. 0aEthnophilosophy. 0aGood and evil. 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 0aSocial change. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBorg, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClough, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClough, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGeschiere, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Hildi J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Jon P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Jon P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTheuma, Nadia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThoden van Velzen, Bonno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerrips, Jojada, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWetering, Imeka van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238756540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782387565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782387565/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_